## Verbatim Quotes

### Quote 1
**Context:** Asked her to describe a recent situation where she was caught off-guard by something academic.

> "Yesterday. Yesterday I found out at 9pm that there was a quiz at 9am the next morning. The professor posted it in Moodle three days ago. I had not opened that course on Moodle in those three days because the professor usually announces things in Teams."

**What this tells us:** Even within a single course, professors are inconsistent about which platform they use for what. Students adapt by checking the platform a professor *usually* uses, which fails when the professor breaks pattern. Pattern-breaking is the failure mode.

---

### Quote 2
**Context:** Asked what she did with that 12 hours.

> "I cried for 20 minutes and then I studied. I called my mom. She told me to go to sleep. I did not."

**What this tells us:** The emotional weight is real and immediate. The pain is not abstract anxiety — it produces tears and family phone calls. This is high intensity, even if low duration.

---

### Quote 3
**Context:** Asked whether she has any system for catching things like this.

> "I have nothing. I gave up trying to have a system. Every system I tried needed me to update it. I am the system now and the system is bad."

**What this tells us:** She has independently arrived at the same insight as VG (kveladze-01) — every system that requires student maintenance fails. She also names herself as the failed system. This is the language of internalized blame for a structural problem.

---

### Quote 4
**Context:** Asked whether her professors know.

> "I think they think Moodle is enough. They post in Moodle and they think they did their job. Maybe technically they did. But nobody only checks Moodle anymore."

**What this tells us:** There is a perception gap between professor mental models (post-and-done) and student reality (multi-platform sweeps). The professor side of this problem is invisible to the professor.

---

## Key Observations

- The "I am the system now and the system is bad" quote is, I think, the single most precise summary of this problem any interviewee has given us.
- She started crying briefly during the quiz story. I paused and asked if she wanted to stop. She said no, that talking about it was actually helping.
- She thanked me at the end of the interview, which has not happened in any of my earlier interviews.

---

## Preliminary Insights

- Intra-course inconsistency (one professor using different platforms for different things) is just as damaging as inter-course inconsistency.
- The emotional cost is acute and immediate — tears, family calls, lost sleep — not just background anxiety.
- Students blame themselves ("I am the system and the system is bad") for what is structurally a platform-fragmentation problem.

